    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1862-09-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1862-09-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="144" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d144">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Adams</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 347.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1862-09-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 15, 1862.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I herewith enclose for your information a
                            copy of a despatch, (No. 214,) of this date, to Mr. Dayton, giving,
                            among other things, the substance of a report recently received from
                            General Shepley, governor of Louisiana, showing the entire freedom of
                            the cotton market in New Orleans.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Francis Adams,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi>
                    </p>
                    <p>(The despatch above referred to is placed, according to date, in the
                                correspondence with France, in this series.)</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
